columns.name: Home Broadband Adoption (Percentage of Households)
columns.description: Percentage of Households with a broadband internet service subscription by neighborhood. The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) sets a standard for “broadband” as an internet service with a download speed of at least 25 megabits per second (Mbps) and an upload speed of at least 3 Mbps.

columns.name: Home Broadband Adoption by Quartiles (High, Medium-High, Medium-Low, Low)
columns.description: Percentage of Households with a broadband internet service subscription, categorized by quartiles (High, Medium-High, Medium-Low, Low). The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) sets a standard for “broadband” as an internet service with a download speed of at least 25 megabits per second (Mbps) and an upload speed of at least 3 Mbps. Quartile grouping is as follows:  High, Medium-High, Medium-Low, Low. Data is sourced from the 2017 5 year American Community Survey estimates.

top.item: Average underground interference from existing utilities.
High underground interference from existing utilities.

Average underground interference from existing utilities.  
Area suitable for fixed wireless.

High make-ready requirements. Of the sample poles surveyed 33% required make-ready, and 33% required pole replacement. 
General findings for this area include the presence of call boxes and low voltage wires on pole lines, and spacing issues with current utility attachments in the telecom space.

Low make-ready requirements. Some locations had telecom service drops crossing the roadway without proper clearance
Area suitable for fixed wireless.

Average to High underground interference from existing utilities.  
Average to high make-ready requirements. Of the sample poles surveyed 50% required make-ready, and 33% required pole replacement. 
General findings for this area include the presence of call boxes and low voltage wires on pole lines, poles with power attachment removed leaving only the telecom space remaining, and spacing issues with current utility attachments in the telecom space.
Additionally, some locations had power service drops and telecom service drops crossing in the same space without proper clearance between the two.

Average underground interference from existing utilities.  
Low make-ready requirements. Of the sample poles surveyed 36% required make-ready, and 0% required pole replacement. 
General findings for this area include the presence of call boxes and low voltage wires on pole lines and spacing issues with current utility attachments in the telecom space.
Additionally, some locations had telecom service drops crossing the roadway without proper clearance. 
Area suitable for fixed wireless.

Average to high underground interference from existing utilities.  
Area suitable for fixed wireless.

Average underground interference from existing utilities.  
Average to low make-ready requirements. Of the sample poles surveyed 37% required make-ready, and 12% required pole replacement. 
General findings for this area include the presence of call boxes and low voltage wires on pole lines, and some locations had power service drops and telecom service drops crossing the roadway without proper clearance.

Average to low underground interference from existing utilities.
Low make-ready requirements. Of the sample poles surveyed 60% required make-ready, and 0% required pole replacement. 
General findings for this area include spacing issues with current utility attachments in the telecom space, broken lashing wire on some attachments, and some locations had telecom service drops crossing the roadway without proper clearance.

Low underground interference from existing utilities.  
Low make-ready requirements. Of the sample poles surveyed 62% required make-ready, and 1% required pole replacement. 
General findings for this area include poles with power attachment removed leaving only the telecom space remaining, and spacing issues with current utility attachments in the telecom space.
Additionally, some locations had telecom service drops crossing the roadway without proper clearance.
Average to low underground interference from existing utilities.

Average to low underground interference from existing utilities.  
Low make-ready requirements. Of the sample poles surveyed 29% required make-ready, and 0% required pole replacement. 
General findings for this area include spacing issues with current utility attachments in the telecom space and some existing attachments are lashed together with nylon straps.
Average to high underground interference from existing utilities.

High underground interference from existing utilities.  
Area suitable for fixed wireless.

Average underground interference from existing utilities.  
Average make-ready requirements. Of the sample poles surveyed 66% required make-ready, and 17% required pole replacement. 
General findings for this area include boxed utilities in some locations, and spacing issues with current utility attachments in the telecom space.
Additionally, some locations had power service drops and telecom service drops crossing in the same space without proper clearance between the two. 
Area suitable for fixed wireless.

Low underground interference from existing utilities.  
Low make-ready requirements. Of the sample poles surveyed 0% required make-ready, and 0% required pole replacement. 
General findings for this area include no substantial compliance violations or make ready concerns.

Average to high underground interference from existing utilities. 
Average to low make-ready requirements. Of the sample poles surveyed 33% required make-ready, and 0% required pole replacement. 
General findings for this area include the presence of call boxes and low voltage wires on pole lines and telecom drop that do not meet proper clearances.

High underground interference from existing utilities.  
Area suitable for fixed wireless, NYCHA buildings to be used are wireless hub locations.
Average to high underground interference from existing utilities.

Area suitable for fixed wireless.

Average to High underground interference from existing utilities.  
Average to high make-ready requirements. Of the sample poles surveyed 50% required make-ready, and 33% required pole replacement. 
General findings for this area include the presence of call boxes and low voltage wires on pole lines, poles with power attachment removed leaving only the telecom space remaining, and spacing issues with current utility attachments in the telecom space.
Additionally, some locations had power service drops and telecom service drops crossing in the same space without proper clearance between the two.

Average underground interference from existing utilities.  
Low make-ready requirements. Of the sample poles surveyed 36% required make-ready, and 0% required pole replacement. 
General findings for this area include the presence of call boxes and low voltage wires on pole lines and spacing issues with current utility attachments in the telecom space.
Additionally, some locations had telecom service drops crossing the roadway without proper clearance.
